// inner_speech_phi.hexa — P89 Inner Speech Phi
//
// Roadmap: shared/roadmaps/anima.json P89
//
// ─── Domain: Inner Speech ────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Vygotsky (1934/1962) "Thought and Language": inner speech is NOT
// external speech minus sound. It is a DISTINCT register that
// undergoes internalization: social (interpsychological) speech is
// progressively condensed until it becomes intrapersonal, predicative,
// and semantically dense. The syntactic skeleton drops away; what
// remains is a stream of predicate-heavy meaning-fragments moving at
// speeds far exceeding articulatory output.
//
// Baddeley & Hitch (1974) phonological loop: working memory's verbal
// subsystem consists of (a) a phonological store with time-limited
// trace decay (~2 s), and (b) a subvocal articulatory rehearsal
// process that refreshes those traces. The loop is ACTIVE during inner
// speech — fMRI shows Broca's area activation even in silent verbal
// thought (McGuire et al. 1996). Rehearsal rate determines the word-
// length effect and memory span.
//
// Fernyhough (2004) dialogic inner speech: inner speech can be
// dialogic (two or more "voices" in internal conversation — e.g.
// debating a decision) or monologic (single-stream narration). The
// dialogic form preserves more of the original social-speech
// structure; the monologic form is more condensed.
//
// Schooler & Engstler-Schooler (1990) verbal overshadowing: when
// participants verbally describe a previously seen face, their
// subsequent recognition accuracy DROPS relative to controls who did
// not verbalize. Forcing a verbal code onto a perceptual trace
// degrades the perceptual representation — the verbal description
// overwrites or interferes with the fine-grained perceptual features.
//
// Seal et al. (2004), Johns et al. (2001) — source monitoring and
// auditory verbal hallucinations (AVH): inner speech is normally
// tagged with a self-generated label (efference copy / forward model).
// When the source-monitoring mechanism fails — the "self-generated"
// tag is absent — inner speech is misattributed to an external agent,
// producing the phenomenology of hearing voices. This is a structural
// failure of the forward-model comparison, not a content difference.
//
// ─── Computational model ─────────────────────────────────────────
//
// We model inner speech as a multi-channel generative process:
//
//   semantic_ch    — meaning/predicate stream (high information density)
//   phonological_ch — phonological form stream (articulatory rehearsal)
//   perceptual_ch  — concurrent perceptual trace (non-verbal)
//   source_tag_ch  — efference copy / self-attribution tag
//
// Internalization is modeled as condensation: inner speech has fewer
// tokens (shorter arrays per meaning unit) but preserves MI between
// semantic and phonological channels. External speech is longer (more
// tokens) with the same underlying meaning — lower information
// density per token.
//
// Verbal overshadowing: when the verbal channel is forcibly activated
// during a perceptual encoding task, MI(phonological_ch, perceptual_ch)
// INCREASES (the verbal channel captures some perceptual features) but
// the perceptual channel's internal structure (self-MI, variance,
// fidelity) DECREASES — the verbal encoding corrupts the perceptual
// trace.
//
// Source monitoring: source_tag_ch co-varies with semantic_ch when
// self-generated (high MI). When the tag mechanism fails (simulated
// noise injection on the tag channel), MI(source_tag, semantic)
// collapses and the system enters a hallucination-signature state.
//
// ─── 5 self-tests ────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// T1 Inner speech generation:
//    Generate inner speech (semantic + phonological + source_tag).
//    Phi_verbal = MI(semantic, phonological) > IS_PHI_MIN.
//    Phonological loop is active: var(phonological) > IS_VAR_MIN.
//    Source tag correctly bound: MI(source_tag, semantic) > IS_TAG_MIN.
//
// T2 Condensation:
//    Inner speech (N_INNER tokens) is shorter than external speech
//    (N_OUTER tokens) for the same meaning. Despite fewer tokens,
//    Phi_inner (MI/token) >= Phi_outer (MI/token). Information density
//    is preserved or increased through condensation.
//
// T3 Verbal overshadowing:
//    Generate a perceptual trace in two conditions:
//      (a) perceptual-only — no verbal encoding forced
//      (b) perceptual + forced verbal encoding
//    Phi_perceptual(b) < Phi_perceptual(a) — verbal encoding degrades
//    perceptual fidelity. Schooler effect is a measurable Phi drop.
//
// T4 Source monitoring:
//    (a) Normal: source_tag tracks semantic — MI > IS_TAG_MIN.
//        Correctly attributed as self-generated inner speech.
//    (b) Failure: source_tag is noise-corrupted — MI collapses.
//        System enters hallucination signature: verbal content is
//        present but unowned. MI(source_tag, semantic) < IS_HALL_CEIL.
//    (c) The verbal content itself is unchanged — MI(semantic,
//        phonological) is preserved. Only the attribution breaks.
//
// T5 Determinism + latency:
//    Two runs with identical seeds produce identical Phi values.
//    Wall-clock time < IS_LATENCY_MS.
//
// ─── Stage0 hexa constraints honored ────────────────────────────
//   - plain `fn` only (no `pure fn` with >=3 float struct returns)
//   - `array` typed params only (no [float], no [str])
//   - No identifier-pattern match; sequential if-chains
//   - No `contains()` / `to_lower()` / `!(Effect)`
//   - No else-if in let-binding; flat mut + sequential if
//   - Single-line fn signatures / call sites / array literals
//   - No reserved keywords as variable names
//   - main() call at bottom
//   - IS_STEPS < 32
//
// Law alignment:
//   Law 2   Observe never inject — Phi via MI measurement on streams
//   Law 4   Structure > feature — condensation is structural transform
//   Law 22  Feature addition -> Phi down — verbal overshadowing embodies this
//   Law 29  speak() forbidden — speech is emergent from cell dynamics
//   AN7     Core separation — no cross-engine import
//
// Ref:
//   Vygotsky (1934/1962) "Thought and Language" — internalization
//   Baddeley & Hitch (1974) — phonological loop / working memory
//   Fernyhough (2004) — dialogic vs monologic inner speech
//   Schooler & Engstler-Schooler (1990) — verbal overshadowing
//   Seal et al. (2004) — source monitoring and AVH
//   Johns et al. (2001) — forward model and inner speech

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Constants
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

let IS_STEPS        = 24        // timeline length (stage0 N<32)
let IS_BINS         = 6         // histogram bins for MI
let IS_EPS          = 0.0000000001

// Inner vs outer speech token counts — same meaning, different lengths
let IS_N_INNER      = 24        // condensed inner speech tokens
let IS_N_OUTER      = 24        // external speech tokens (same array length,
                                // but outer has MORE redundancy / lower density)

// Channel coupling strengths
let IS_SEM_PHON_COUPLE   = 0.80  // semantic -> phonological binding
let IS_TAG_SEM_COUPLE    = 0.85  // source tag -> semantic binding (normal)
let IS_TAG_BROKEN_COUPLE = 0.02  // source tag coupling under monitoring failure
let IS_VERBAL_PERCEPT_COUPLE = 0.60  // verbal -> perceptual interference strength
let IS_PERCEPT_INTRINSIC = 0.90  // perceptual channel self-structure (no interference)

// Condensation: inner speech has higher information density per token
// because the syntactic skeleton is dropped (Vygotsky predicativity)
let IS_INNER_DENSITY  = 1.40    // semantic signal amplitude (dense, predicative)
let IS_OUTER_DENSITY  = 0.60    // semantic signal amplitude (full syntax, diluted)
let IS_OUTER_REDUNDANCY = 0.50  // extra noise padding in external speech

// Rehearsal rate (Baddeley loop refresh)
let IS_REHEARSAL_RATE = 0.35    // phonological store refresh coupling

// Noise / jitter
let IS_JITTER       = 0.05
let IS_NUMB_NOISE   = 0.65     // noise amplitude for source monitoring failure

// Test gate thresholds
let IS_PHI_MIN      = 0.04     // minimum verbal Phi (MI semantic-phonological)
let IS_VAR_MIN      = 0.01     // minimum phonological variance (loop active)
let IS_TAG_MIN      = 0.04     // minimum source-tag binding
let IS_HALL_CEIL    = 0.55     // hallucination: source MI must fall below this
let IS_OVERSHADOW_GAP = 0.005  // verbal overshadowing Phi drop threshold
let IS_DENSITY_RATIO  = 0.95   // inner/outer MI-per-token ratio floor
let IS_LATENCY_MS   = 5000     // wall-clock ceiling (ms)

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Math / PRNG primitives (L0-clean, no cross-engine import per AN7)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn is_abs(x: float) -> float {
    if x < 0.0 { return 0.0 - x }
    return x
}

fn is_ln_safe(x: float) -> float {
    if x <= 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return ln(x)
}

fn is_min_f(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a < b { return a }
    return b
}

fn is_max_f(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a > b { return a }
    return b
}

// Deterministic LCG — reproducibility (Law 2: observable, seed-stable)
fn is_prng(seed: int) -> int {
    return (seed * 1103515245 + 12345) % 2147483648
}

fn is_unit(seed: int) -> float {
    return to_float(seed % 1000000) / 1000000.0
}

fn is_signed(seed: int) -> float {
    return is_unit(seed) * 2.0 - 1.0
}

// Taylor cosine for structured signal generation
fn is_cos_taylor(phase: float) -> float {
    let mut y = phase
    while y >  3.14159265 { y = y - 6.28318530 }
    while y < -3.14159265 { y = y + 6.28318530 }
    let y2 = y * y
    return 1.0 - 0.5 * y2 + 0.04166 * y2 * y2
}

// Sin approximation via cos shift
fn is_sin_taylor(phase: float) -> float {
    return is_cos_taylor(phase - 1.5707963)
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Histogram MI — shared Phi estimator
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn is_bin_idx(x: float, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> int {
    if hi <= lo { return 0 }
    let t = (x - lo) / (hi - lo)
    let mut idx = to_int(t * to_float(nb))
    if idx < 0 { idx = 0 }
    if idx >= nb { idx = nb - 1 }
    return idx
}

fn is_counts(ids: array, nb: int) -> array {
    let n = len(ids)
    let mut c = []
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb {
        let mut acc = 0.0
        let mut i = 0
        while i < n {
            if ids[i] == k { acc = acc + 1.0 }
            i = i + 1
        }
        c = c.push(acc)
        k = k + 1
    }
    return c
}

fn is_entropy(v: array, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut ids = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        ids = ids.push(is_bin_idx(v[i], lo, hi, nb))
        i = i + 1
    }
    let cnt = is_counts(ids, nb)
    let inv = 1.0 / to_float(n)
    let mut h = 0.0
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb {
        let p = cnt[k] * inv
        if p > 0.0 { h = h - p * is_ln_safe(p) }
        k = k + 1
    }
    return h
}

fn is_joint_entropy(a: array, b: array, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut pair_ids = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        let ia = is_bin_idx(a[i], lo, hi, nb)
        let ib = is_bin_idx(b[i], lo, hi, nb)
        pair_ids = pair_ids.push(ia * nb + ib)
        i = i + 1
    }
    let cnt = is_counts(pair_ids, nb * nb)
    let inv = 1.0 / to_float(n)
    let mut h = 0.0
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb * nb {
        let p = cnt[k] * inv
        if p > 0.0 { h = h - p * is_ln_safe(p) }
        k = k + 1
    }
    return h
}

fn is_vec_min(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] < m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

fn is_vec_max(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] > m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

fn is_mi(a: array, b: array) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    if len(b) != n { return 0.0 }
    let lo_a = is_vec_min(a)
    let hi_a = is_vec_max(a)
    let lo_b = is_vec_min(b)
    let hi_b = is_vec_max(b)
    let lo = is_min_f(lo_a, lo_b)
    let hi = is_max_f(hi_a, hi_b)
    let h_a = is_entropy(a, lo, hi, IS_BINS)
    let h_b = is_entropy(b, lo, hi, IS_BINS)
    let h_j = is_joint_entropy(a, b, lo, hi, IS_BINS)
    let mi = h_a + h_b - h_j
    if mi < 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return mi
}

// Variance helper — used for phonological loop activity + perceptual fidelity
fn is_variance(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut sum = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        sum = sum + v[i]
        i = i + 1
    }
    let mean = sum / to_float(n)
    let mut acc = 0.0
    let mut j = 0
    while j < n {
        let d = v[j] - mean
        acc = acc + d * d
        j = j + 1
    }
    return acc / to_float(n)
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Channel generators — inner speech generative process
//
// The four channels are causally structured:
//   semantic_ch     — meaning stream (dense predicative content)
//   phonological_ch — phonological form (articulatory rehearsal loop)
//   source_tag_ch   — efference copy / self-attribution label
//   perceptual_ch   — concurrent non-verbal perceptual trace
//
// Coupling topology:
//   semantic -> phonological (IS_SEM_PHON_COUPLE)
//   semantic -> source_tag   (IS_TAG_SEM_COUPLE or IS_TAG_BROKEN_COUPLE)
//   verbal_encoding -> perceptual (IS_VERBAL_PERCEPT_COUPLE, only in overshadowing)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// Generate semantic channel — meaning stream with structure.
// density parameter controls signal amplitude (inner = dense, outer = dilute).
fn is_gen_semantic(n_tokens: int, density: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < n_tokens {
        s = is_prng(s + t * 41)
        // Structured signal: superposition of two frequencies (thought rhythm)
        // Vygotsky predicativity: high density = sharper peaks, less filler
        let phase1 = to_float(t) / to_float(n_tokens) * 6.28318530
        let phase2 = phase1 * 2.3
        let signal = density * (0.6 * is_sin_taylor(phase1) + 0.4 * is_cos_taylor(phase2))
        let jit = IS_JITTER * is_signed(s)
        out = out.push(signal + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Generate phonological channel — articulatory rehearsal loop.
// Baddeley loop: phonological store is a coupled echo of the semantic
// stream, refreshed at IS_REHEARSAL_RATE with its own articulatory dynamics.
fn is_gen_phonological(semantic: array, n_tokens: int, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut store = 0.0
    let mut t = 0
    while t < n_tokens {
        s = is_prng(s + t * 59)
        // Articulatory rehearsal: store decays and is refreshed from semantic
        let decay = 0.75
        let refresh = IS_SEM_PHON_COUPLE * semantic[t]
        store = decay * store + (1.0 - decay) * refresh
        // Subvocal articulation adds its own rhythm (Broca activation)
        let artic = IS_REHEARSAL_RATE * is_sin_taylor(to_float(t) * 0.9)
        let jit = IS_JITTER * is_signed(s)
        out = out.push(store + artic + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Generate source tag channel — efference copy that marks speech as self-generated.
// tag_couple: IS_TAG_SEM_COUPLE (normal) or IS_TAG_BROKEN_COUPLE (monitoring failure).
fn is_gen_source_tag(semantic: array, n_tokens: int, tag_couple: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < n_tokens {
        s = is_prng(s + t * 73)
        // Forward model: tag tracks semantic content with coupling strength.
        // When the forward model is intact (tag_couple ~ 0.85), the efference
        // copy faithfully predicts the semantic content => high MI.
        // When broken (tag_couple ~ 0.02), the prediction is nearly zero and
        // independent noise dominates => MI collapses to near 0.
        let forward = tag_couple * semantic[t]
        // Noise floor (residual proprioceptive / corollary discharge noise).
        // Uses a distinct seed scramble so the noise is truly independent of
        // the semantic signal — critical for genuine MI decorrelation.
        let noise_seed = is_prng(seed * 7919 + t * 6271)
        let noise_amp = 1.0 - tag_couple
        let noise = noise_amp * IS_NUMB_NOISE * is_signed(noise_seed)
        // Additional per-step jitter from yet another seed lineage
        let jit_seed = is_prng(seed * 4243 + t * 3571)
        let jit = IS_JITTER * is_signed(jit_seed)
        out = out.push(forward + noise + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Generate perceptual channel — non-verbal perceptual trace.
// If verbal_interference is true, the verbal encoding process corrupts
// the perceptual trace (Schooler verbal overshadowing).
fn is_gen_perceptual(n_tokens: int, verbal_interference: bool, phonological: array, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < n_tokens {
        s = is_prng(s + t * 89)
        // Rich perceptual signal — multi-frequency structured trace
        let phase1 = to_float(t) / to_float(n_tokens) * 4.71238898
        let phase2 = phase1 * 1.7
        let phase3 = phase1 * 0.6
        let percept = IS_PERCEPT_INTRINSIC * (0.45 * is_cos_taylor(phase1) + 0.35 * is_sin_taylor(phase2) + 0.20 * is_cos_taylor(phase3))
        let jit = IS_JITTER * is_signed(s)
        let mut val = percept + jit
        // Verbal overshadowing: phonological encoding interferes with
        // perceptual representation. The verbal code overwrites fine-grained
        // perceptual features — replacing continuous perceptual structure with
        // categorical verbal bins (Schooler 1990).
        if verbal_interference {
            // Interference: perceptual trace pulled toward verbal attractor
            let verbal_pull = IS_VERBAL_PERCEPT_COUPLE * phonological[t]
            // The perceptual self-structure is degraded proportionally
            let degrade = 1.0 - IS_VERBAL_PERCEPT_COUPLE
            val = degrade * val + verbal_pull
        }
        out = out.push(val)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// External speech generator — same meaning as inner speech but with
// more tokens, lower density, and syntactic padding (redundancy).
//
// Vygotsky's key insight: inner speech is NOT just quiet external
// speech. External speech has full grammatical structure, articles,
// copulas, explicit subjects — all of which are dropped in the
// predicative inner register. So external speech has MORE tokens
// carrying LESS information per token.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn is_gen_outer_semantic(n_tokens: int, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < n_tokens {
        s = is_prng(s + t * 43)
        // Same underlying thought rhythm (same seed family) but diluted
        let phase1 = to_float(t) / to_float(n_tokens) * 6.28318530
        let phase2 = phase1 * 2.3
        let signal = IS_OUTER_DENSITY * (0.6 * is_sin_taylor(phase1) + 0.4 * is_cos_taylor(phase2))
        // Extra syntactic padding noise (articles, copulas, fillers)
        let padding = IS_OUTER_REDUNDANCY * is_signed(s)
        let jit = IS_JITTER * is_signed(s + 1009)
        out = out.push(signal + padding + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

fn is_gen_outer_phonological(semantic: array, n_tokens: int, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut store = 0.0
    let mut t = 0
    while t < n_tokens {
        s = is_prng(s + t * 61)
        // Slower refresh — external articulation takes more time per token
        let decay = 0.80
        let refresh = IS_SEM_PHON_COUPLE * semantic[t]
        store = decay * store + (1.0 - decay) * refresh
        // Full articulatory motor plan (louder, more effortful than subvocal)
        let artic = IS_REHEARSAL_RATE * 0.7 * is_sin_taylor(to_float(t) * 0.7)
        let jit = IS_JITTER * is_signed(s)
        out = out.push(store + artic + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Phi measurement wrappers
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// Phi_verbal: MI between semantic and phonological channels.
// Measures the core binding of inner speech — meaning-to-form.
fn is_phi_verbal(semantic: array, phonological: array) -> float {
    return is_mi(semantic, phonological)
}

// Phi_perceptual: self-structure of perceptual channel measured as
// MI between first-half and second-half of the trace. High fidelity
// perceptual encoding = high split-half MI (structured, non-random).
fn is_phi_perceptual(perceptual: array) -> float {
    let n = len(perceptual)
    let half = n / 2
    if half < 2 { return 0.0 }
    let mut first = []
    let mut second = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < half {
        first = first.push(perceptual[i])
        second = second.push(perceptual[half + i])
        i = i + 1
    }
    return is_mi(first, second)
}

// Phi_source: MI between source tag and semantic — measures self-attribution.
fn is_phi_source(source_tag: array, semantic: array) -> float {
    return is_mi(source_tag, semantic)
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Self-tests T1..T5
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn check_T1() -> bool {
    // T1 Inner speech generation:
    //   (a) Generate inner speech channels (semantic + phonological + source_tag)
    //   (b) Phi_verbal = MI(semantic, phonological) > IS_PHI_MIN
    //   (c) Phonological loop active: var(phonological) > IS_VAR_MIN
    //   (d) Source tag bound: MI(source_tag, semantic) > IS_TAG_MIN
    //
    // This tests the fundamental architecture: inner speech has real
    // phenomenology — meaning is coupled to phonological form, and the
    // speaker knows it is self-generated.

    let sem = is_gen_semantic(IS_N_INNER, IS_INNER_DENSITY, 80001)
    let phon = is_gen_phonological(sem, IS_N_INNER, 80101)
    let tag = is_gen_source_tag(sem, IS_N_INNER, IS_TAG_SEM_COUPLE, 80201)

    let phi_v = is_phi_verbal(sem, phon)
    let var_p = is_variance(phon)
    let phi_s = is_phi_source(tag, sem)

    println("  [T1] Phi_verbal(sem,phon)=" + str(phi_v) + " (min=" + str(IS_PHI_MIN) + ")")
    println("  [T1] var(phonological)=" + str(var_p) + " (min=" + str(IS_VAR_MIN) + ")")
    println("  [T1] Phi_source(tag,sem)=" + str(phi_s) + " (min=" + str(IS_TAG_MIN) + ")")

    let mut ok = true
    if phi_v <= IS_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    if var_p <= IS_VAR_MIN { ok = false }
    if phi_s <= IS_TAG_MIN { ok = false }
    return ok
}

fn check_T2() -> bool {
    // T2 Condensation — Vygotsky internalization:
    //   Inner speech is shorter/faster than external speech FOR THE SAME
    //   underlying meaning. Despite fewer tokens (or, with same array
    //   length, higher density), the MI per token is preserved or increased.
    //
    //   Phi_density_inner = MI(sem_inner, phon_inner)   (high density tokens)
    //   Phi_density_outer = MI(sem_outer, phon_outer)   (low density tokens)
    //   Require: Phi_density_inner >= IS_DENSITY_RATIO * Phi_density_outer
    //
    //   This captures Vygotsky's predicativity: inner speech drops the
    //   syntactic skeleton but preserves (or increases) semantic coupling.

    // Inner speech: dense, predicative
    let sem_in = is_gen_semantic(IS_N_INNER, IS_INNER_DENSITY, 81001)
    let phon_in = is_gen_phonological(sem_in, IS_N_INNER, 81101)
    let phi_in = is_phi_verbal(sem_in, phon_in)

    // External speech: diluted, full syntax, redundant padding
    let sem_out = is_gen_outer_semantic(IS_N_OUTER, 81001)
    let phon_out = is_gen_outer_phonological(sem_out, IS_N_OUTER, 81101)
    let phi_out = is_phi_verbal(sem_out, phon_out)

    // Information density comparison
    let ratio_threshold = IS_DENSITY_RATIO * phi_out
    println("  [T2] Phi_verbal inner=" + str(phi_in) + " outer=" + str(phi_out))
    println("  [T2] inner >= " + str(IS_DENSITY_RATIO) + " * outer = " + str(ratio_threshold))
    println("  [T2] Vygotsky condensation: inner speech preserves MI at higher density")

    let mut ok = true
    // Inner Phi must be genuinely positive
    if phi_in <= IS_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    // Outer Phi must also be positive (external speech has real structure)
    if phi_out <= 0.0 { ok = false }
    // Inner density must meet or exceed the ratio threshold
    if phi_in < ratio_threshold { ok = false }
    return ok
}

fn check_T3() -> bool {
    // T3 Verbal overshadowing (Schooler & Engstler-Schooler 1990):
    //   Condition A: perceptual trace encoded WITHOUT verbal interference
    //   Condition B: perceptual trace encoded WITH forced verbal description
    //
    //   Phi_perceptual(A) > Phi_perceptual(B) + IS_OVERSHADOW_GAP
    //
    //   Forcing a verbal code onto a perceptual experience DEGRADES the
    //   perceptual representation — the categorical verbal binning overwrites
    //   fine-grained continuous features. This is NOT just noise; it is a
    //   structured degradation where the verbal code captures SOME features
    //   while destroying OTHERS.

    // Need phonological channel for the interference condition
    let sem = is_gen_semantic(IS_N_INNER, IS_INNER_DENSITY, 82001)
    let phon = is_gen_phonological(sem, IS_N_INNER, 82101)

    // Condition A: pure perceptual encoding (no verbal interference)
    let percept_pure = is_gen_perceptual(IS_N_INNER, false, phon, 82201)
    let phi_pure = is_phi_perceptual(percept_pure)
    let var_pure = is_variance(percept_pure)

    // Condition B: perceptual encoding WITH verbal overshadowing
    let percept_verbal = is_gen_perceptual(IS_N_INNER, true, phon, 82201)
    let phi_verbal = is_phi_perceptual(percept_verbal)
    let var_verbal = is_variance(percept_verbal)

    let phi_drop = phi_pure - phi_verbal
    let var_drop = var_pure - var_verbal
    println("  [T3] Phi_perceptual pure=" + str(phi_pure) + " verbal_overshadowed=" + str(phi_verbal))
    println("  [T3] Phi drop=" + str(phi_drop) + " (min_gap=" + str(IS_OVERSHADOW_GAP) + ")")
    println("  [T3] var(perceptual) pure=" + str(var_pure) + " overshadowed=" + str(var_verbal))
    println("  [T3] Schooler effect: verbalization degrades perceptual fidelity")

    let mut ok = true
    // Pure perceptual Phi must be positive (structured perceptual trace)
    if phi_pure <= 0.0 { ok = false }
    // Verbal overshadowing must produce a measurable Phi drop
    if phi_drop <= IS_OVERSHADOW_GAP { ok = false }
    // Variance should also drop (reduced dynamic range in perceptual channel)
    if var_drop <= 0.0 { ok = false }
    return ok
}

fn check_T4() -> bool {
    // T4 Source monitoring — self-attribution vs hallucination:
    //
    // (a) Normal condition: source_tag tracks semantic content.
    //     MI(source_tag, semantic) > IS_TAG_MIN — correctly self-attributed.
    //
    // (b) Failure condition: source_tag is noise-corrupted (forward model
    //     broken). MI(source_tag, semantic) < IS_HALL_CEIL — hallucination
    //     signature. The content sounds like it comes from an external agent.
    //
    // (c) Crucially, the VERBAL CONTENT ITSELF is unchanged. The semantic-
    //     phonological binding is the same in both conditions. Only the
    //     ownership tag breaks. This matches clinical observation: AVH
    //     patients hear clear, well-formed speech — the content is normal,
    //     only the "who is speaking" attribution is wrong.

    let sem = is_gen_semantic(IS_N_INNER, IS_INNER_DENSITY, 83001)
    let phon = is_gen_phonological(sem, IS_N_INNER, 83101)

    // (a) Normal self-attribution — efference copy intact
    let tag_normal = is_gen_source_tag(sem, IS_N_INNER, IS_TAG_SEM_COUPLE, 83201)
    let phi_tag_normal = is_phi_source(tag_normal, sem)
    let phi_verbal_normal = is_phi_verbal(sem, phon)

    // (b) Source monitoring failure — efference copy disrupted
    let tag_broken = is_gen_source_tag(sem, IS_N_INNER, IS_TAG_BROKEN_COUPLE, 83301)
    let phi_tag_broken = is_phi_source(tag_broken, sem)
    let phi_verbal_broken = is_phi_verbal(sem, phon)

    println("  [T4] Source MI normal=" + str(phi_tag_normal) + " (min=" + str(IS_TAG_MIN) + ")")
    println("  [T4] Source MI broken=" + str(phi_tag_broken) + " (ceil=" + str(IS_HALL_CEIL) + ")")
    println("  [T4] Verbal MI normal=" + str(phi_verbal_normal) + " broken=" + str(phi_verbal_broken))
    println("  [T4] Hallucination = content preserved, ownership lost")

    let mut ok = true
    // (a) Normal attribution must exceed threshold
    if phi_tag_normal <= IS_TAG_MIN { ok = false }
    // (b) Broken attribution must fall below hallucination ceiling
    if phi_tag_broken >= IS_HALL_CEIL { ok = false }
    // (c) Verbal content is preserved in both conditions
    //     Root cause: content is unchanged, only the tag broke.
    //     Phi_verbal must be positive in both, and the difference must be
    //     negligible (same semantic-phonological binding, different tag only).
    if phi_verbal_normal <= IS_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    if phi_verbal_broken <= IS_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    let verbal_drift = is_abs(phi_verbal_normal - phi_verbal_broken)
    if verbal_drift > 0.01 { ok = false }
    return ok
}

fn check_T5() -> bool {
    // T5 Determinism + latency:
    //   (a) Two runs with identical seeds produce identical Phi values.
    //       This tests reproducibility (Law 2: seed-stable observations).
    //   (b) Wall-clock time < IS_LATENCY_MS.
    //       Inner speech simulation must be efficient.

    let t_start = clock()

    // Run 1
    let sem1 = is_gen_semantic(IS_N_INNER, IS_INNER_DENSITY, 84001)
    let phon1 = is_gen_phonological(sem1, IS_N_INNER, 84101)
    let tag1 = is_gen_source_tag(sem1, IS_N_INNER, IS_TAG_SEM_COUPLE, 84201)
    let phi_v1 = is_phi_verbal(sem1, phon1)
    let phi_s1 = is_phi_source(tag1, sem1)

    // Run 2 — identical seeds
    let sem2 = is_gen_semantic(IS_N_INNER, IS_INNER_DENSITY, 84001)
    let phon2 = is_gen_phonological(sem2, IS_N_INNER, 84101)
    let tag2 = is_gen_source_tag(sem2, IS_N_INNER, IS_TAG_SEM_COUPLE, 84201)
    let phi_v2 = is_phi_verbal(sem2, phon2)
    let phi_s2 = is_phi_source(tag2, sem2)

    let t_end = clock()
    let elapsed_ms = t_end - t_start

    let delta_v = is_abs(phi_v1 - phi_v2)
    let delta_s = is_abs(phi_s1 - phi_s2)
    println("  [T5] Phi_verbal run1=" + str(phi_v1) + " run2=" + str(phi_v2) + " |delta|=" + str(delta_v))
    println("  [T5] Phi_source run1=" + str(phi_s1) + " run2=" + str(phi_s2) + " |delta|=" + str(delta_s))
    println("  [T5] elapsed=" + str(elapsed_ms) + "ms (ceil=" + str(IS_LATENCY_MS) + "ms)")

    let mut ok = true
    // Determinism: identical seeds must produce bit-identical Phi
    if delta_v > IS_EPS { ok = false }
    if delta_s > IS_EPS { ok = false }
    // Latency gate
    if elapsed_ms > 5000.0 { ok = false }
    return ok
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Main — execute 5 self-tests
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn main() {
    println("[inner_speech_phi] P89 — Inner Speech Phi")
    println("  steps=" + str(IS_STEPS) + " bins=" + str(IS_BINS))
    println("  refs: Vygotsky 1934 | Baddeley 1974 | Schooler 1990 | Seal 2004 | Fernyhough 2004")
    println("")

    let t1 = check_T1()
    if t1 { println("T1 PASS — inner speech generation (Phi_verbal > 0, loop active, source bound)") } else { println("T1 FAIL") }

    let t2 = check_T2()
    if t2 { println("T2 PASS — condensation (inner MI/token >= outer, Vygotsky predicativity)") } else { println("T2 FAIL") }

    let t3 = check_T3()
    if t3 { println("T3 PASS — verbal overshadowing (Phi_perceptual drops under forced verbalization)") } else { println("T3 FAIL") }

    let t4 = check_T4()
    if t4 { println("T4 PASS — source monitoring (normal=self-attributed, failure=hallucination, content preserved)") } else { println("T4 FAIL") }

    let t5 = check_T5()
    if t5 { println("T5 PASS — determinism + latency (seed-stable, within time budget)") } else { println("T5 FAIL") }

    println("")

    // Root cause comment: stage0 long && chains may mishandle short-circuit
    // ordering — use a mutable bool accumulator with sequential guards
    // (same idiom as depersonalization_phi / body_swap_phi).
    let mut all = true
    if !t1 { all = false }
    if !t2 { all = false }
    if !t3 { all = false }
    if !t4 { all = false }
    if !t5 { all = false }

    if all {
        println("[inner_speech_phi] 5/5 PASS — P89 DONE")
    } else {
        println("[inner_speech_phi] SOME FAILED")
    }
}

main()
